scRNA-seq analysis with Seurat

scRNA-seq analysis following “Seurat - Guided Clustering Tutorial”
Single Cell Gene Expression Data from 10X Genomics
“7.5k Sorted Cells from Human Invasive Ductal Carcinoma, 3’ v3.1”

Jeamin Jung, updated Jun 2023

install.packages('Seurat')
library(Seurat)
library(Matrix)
library(dplyr)
raw_bc_data <- Read10X(data.dir = "/Users/jeamin/Desktop/analysis_prac/analysis_visuals/raw_feature_bc_matrix")
# saving memory
dense.size <- object.size(x = as.matrix(x = raw_bc_data))
sparse.size <- object.size(x = raw_bc_data)
dense.size/sparse.size
# Iitializing the Seurat Object, filtering for any genes not expressed in atleast 3 cells and without atleast 100 features expressed in the cell
bc_3p_lt <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = raw_bc_data, min.cells = 3, min.features = 100, project = "10X_BC")
bc_3p_lt

bc_3p_lt[["percent.mt"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(bc_3p_lt, pattern = "^MT-")
# Show QC metrics for the first 5 cells
head(bc_3p_lt@meta.data, 5)
# Visualize QC metrics as a violin plot
VlnPlot(bc_3p_lt, features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA", "percent.mt"), ncol = 3)

plot1 <- FeatureScatter(bc_3p_lt, feature1 = "nCount_RNA", feature2 = "percent.mt")
plot2 <- FeatureScatter(bc_3p_lt, feature1 = "nCount_RNA", feature2 = "nFeature_RNA")

bc_3p_lt_subset <- subset(bc_3p_lt, subset = (nFeature_RNA > 200 & nFeature_RNA < 2500) & percent.mt < 5)
# normalizing the data
bc_3p_lt_subset <- NormalizeData(bc_3p_lt_subset, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", scale.factor = 10000)

# Visualizing cells and features that define PCA in different ways:
# 1. 
VizDimLoadings(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims = 1:2, reduction = "pca")

DimPlot(bc_3p_lt_subset, reduction = "pca")

# 3.
DimHeatmap(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims=1, cells=500, balanced=TRUE)

DimHeatmap(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims=1:5, cells=500, balanced=TRUE)

# Determining the dimensionality of the dataset
bc_3p_lt_subset <- JackStraw(bc_3p_lt_subset, num.replicate = 100)
bc_3p_lt_subset <- ScoreJackStraw(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims=1:20)
# "‘Significant’ PCs will show a strong enrichment of features with low p-values (solid curve above the dashed line)."
JackStrawPlot(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims=1:15)
Warning: Removed 21000 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

# Alternative method
ElbowPlot(bc_3p_lt_subset)

# Clustering the cells
bc_3p_lt_subset <- FindNeighbors(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims=1:10)
bc_3p_lt_subset <- FindClusters(bc_3p_lt_subset, resolution = 0.5)
bc_3p_lt_subset <- RunUMAP(bc_3p_lt_subset, dims = 1:10)
DimPlot(bc_3p_lt_subset, reduction='umap', label=TRUE)

# Finding differentially expressed biomarkers (cluster biomarkers)
# 
cluster2.markers <- FindMarkers(bc_3p_lt_subset, ident.1 = 2, min.pct = 0.25)
head(cluster2.markers, n=5)
# Finding markers distinguishing cluster 2 from cluster 0 and cluster 1 
cluster2.markers <- FindMarkers(bc_3p_lt_subset, ident.1 = 2, ident.2 = c(0, 1), min.pct = 0.25)
head(cluster2.markers, n = 5)
FeaturePlot(bc_3p_lt_subset, features = c("VIM", "GSTP1", "ANXA1", "PLIN2", "AKAP13"))

# find markers for every cluster compared to all remaining cells, report only the positive ones
bc_3p_lt_subset.markers <- FindAllMarkers(bc_3p_lt_subset, only.pos = TRUE, min.pct = 0.25, logfc.threshold = 0.25)
bc_3p_lt_subset.markers %>%
    group_by(cluster) %>%
    slice_max(n = 2, order_by = avg_log2FC)
FeaturePlot(bc_3p_lt_subset, features = c("RGS5", "KRT19", "RPS2", "FTH1", "VIM", "HLA-DRA"))

bc_3p_lt_subset.markers %>%
    group_by(cluster) %>%
    top_n(n = 10, wt = avg_log2FC) -> top10
DoHeatmap(bc_3p_lt_subset, features = top10$gene)
